HEADWORD: Size
<hw>Size</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Sice</er>, and
<er>Sise</er>.]</ety> <def>Six.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Size</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Size
<hw>Size</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OIt. <ets>sisa</ets>
glue used by painters, shortened fr. <ets>assisa</ets>, fr.
<ets>assidere</ets>, p. p. <ets>assiso</ets>, to make to sit, to seat,
to place, L. <ets>assidere</ets> to sit down; <ets>ad</ets> +
<ets>sidere</ets> to sit down, akin to <ets>sedere</ets> to sit. See
<er>Sit</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos>, and cf. <er>Assize</er>, <er>Size</er>
bulk.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A thin, weak glue used in various trades,
as in painting, bookbinding, paper making, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Any viscous substance, as gilder's
varnish.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Size</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Size
<hw>Size</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Sized</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Sizing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To cover with size; to prepare
with size.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Size</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Size
<hw>Size</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Abbrev. from <ets>assize</ets>. See
<er>Assize</er>, and cf. <er>Size</er> glue.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A
settled quantity or allowance. See <er>Assize</er>.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧To scant my <xex>sizes</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Univ. of Cambridge, Eng.)</fld> <def>An allowance
of food and drink from the buttery, aside from the regular dinner at
commons; -- corresponding to <xex>battel</xex> at Oxford.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Extent of superficies or volume; bulk; bigness;
magnitude; <as>as, the <ex>size</ex> of a tree or of a mast; the
<ex>size</ex> of a ship or of a rock</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Figurative bulk; condition as to rank, ability,
character, etc.; <as>as, the office demands a man of larger
<ex>size</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Men of a less <qex>size</qex> and quality.</q>
<rj><qau>L'Estrange.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The middling or lower <qex>size</qex> of people.</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A conventional relative measure of dimension, as for
shoes, gloves, and other articles made up for sale.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>An instrument consisting of a number of perforated
gauges fastened together at one end by a rivet, -- used for ascertaining
the size of pearls.</def> <rj><au>Knight.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Size roll</b></col>, <cd>a small piese of parchment added
to a roll.</cd> -- <col><b>Size stick</b></col>, <cd>a measuring stick
used by shoemakers for ascertaining the size of the foot.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Dimension; bigness; largeness; greatness;
magnitude.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Size</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Size
<hw>Size</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To fix the standard
of.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧To <xex>size</xex> weights and measures.⟦rdquo⟧
<mark>[R.]</mark> <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To adjust or arrange according to size or
bulk.</def> Specifically: <sd>(a)</sd> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>To take
the height of men, in order to place them in the ranks according to
their stature.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(Mining)</fld> <def>To sift, as
pieces of ore or metal, in order to separate the finer from the coarser
parts.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To swell; to increase the bulk of.</def>
<rj><au>Beau. & Fl.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Mech.)</fld> <def>To bring or adjust anything
exactly to a required dimension, as by cutting.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<cs><p><col><b>To size up</b></col>, <cd>to estimate or ascertain the
character and ability of. See 4th <er>Size</er>, 4.</cd> <mark>[Slang,
U.S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We had <qex>to size up</qex> our fellow legislators.</q>
<rj><qau>The Century.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p></cs>

<p><ent>Size</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 6 ====
HEADWORD: Size
<hw>Size</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To take greater size;
to increase in size.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Our desires give them fashion, and so,⟦br⟧
As they wax lesser, fall, as they <qex>size</qex>, grow.</q>
<rj><qau>Donne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Univ. of Cambridge, Eng.)</fld> <def>To order food
or drink from the buttery; hence, to enter a score, as upon the buttery
book.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sized</ent>⟦br⟧
